      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The moral imperative to prevent mass atrocities is a foundational principle of modern international law, and failing to act when genocide is imminent is a profound moral failure. The argument that one must prioritize theoretical future instability over the immediate, certain death of innocent civilians is a morally bankrupt justification. The intervention, in that narrow moment, was a necessary moral success because it upheld the fundamental duty to protect human life from immediate slaughter.",
      "source": "target",
